Nods for Best Picture - The King's Speech
2011-01-30 05:52:35 GMT
Director Tom Hooper's story of how King George VI found his voice when England found itself facing war with Nazi Germany was brought to life by a lively cast. Colin Firth, Helena Bonham Carter and Geoffrey Rush all received nominations for their roles in the film.The King's Speech is a 2010 British historical drama film directed by Tom Hooper and written by David Seidler. The film won the 2010 Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award.The film stars Colin Firth as King George VI and Geoffrey Rush as speech therapist Lionel Logue, who helped George VI overcome a stammer. Filming commenced in the United Kingdom in November 2009. The film was given a limited release in the United States on 26 November 2010 before giving it a wide release on 10 December 2010 and it was given general release across the UK on 7 January 2011. It received 12 Academy Award nominations, including Best Picture, Actor (Firth), Director (Hooper) and Original Screenplay (Seidler), Supporting Actress (Bonham Carter) and Supporting Actor (Rush) .
